<sections title="EclipseLink 2.4.0  (Juno) Release">

	<section class="title">
		<description>
			<h1>EclipseLink 2.4.0 - Juno</h1>
			<p> The EclipseLink 2.4 release builds on the
				increased developer
				flexibility and multitenant features first
				introduced in 2.3.
				EclipseLink now offers support for NoSQL, REST, JSON as well as
				additional tenant isolation modes for PaaS and SaaS cloud enabled
				application development.
			</p>
		</description>
	</section>

	<section class="main" name=" New and Noteworthy" image="/sequoyah/images/CC_news.png">

		<description>

			<table>
				<tr>
					<td colspan="2">
						<h4>RESTFul Persistence with JPA-RS</h4>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr
					style="padding:0.5em;margin:0.5em 0.5em 1em 1em;border:1px solid #D9D9D9;background:#EFEFEF;-moz-border-radius:4px;">
					<td valign="top">
						Developers using EclipseLink in their applications
						can now simply add the JPA-RS web fragment library into their web
						applications and get the automated exposure of a REST access that
						exposes their persistence unit with entities being implicitly
						converted into JSON or XML within the REST operations.
					</td>
					<td width="150">
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/doc_small.png" />
							<a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Development/2.4.0/JPA-RS">Documentation</a>
						</div>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td colspan="2">
						<h4>Tenant Isolation by Table, Schema, or Data Source</h4>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr
					style="padding:0.5em;margin:0.5em 0.5em 1em 1em;border:1px solid #D9D9D9;background:#EFEFEF;-moz-border-radius:4px;">
					<td valign="top">
						Developers can design and deploy applications where
						their persistent entities
						manage entities for multiple tenants in
						the same application with
						storage in tables per tenant uniquely
						identified by name or
						schema. Developers can now alternatively have
						their applications customize the data source used for different
						tenant's application instances.
					</td>
					<td>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/doc_small.png" />
							<a
								href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/DesignDocs/Multi-Tenancy/TablePerTenant">Documentation</a>
						</div>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/wiki_small.png" />
							<a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Examples/JPA/Multitenant">Examples</a>
						</div>
					</td>
				</tr>

				<tr>
					<td colspan="2">
						<h4>NoSQL</h4>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr
					style="padding:0.5em;margin:0.5em 0.5em 1em 1em;border:1px solid #D9D9D9;background:#EFEFEF;-moz-border-radius:4px;">
					<td valign="top">
						Integration NoSQL data stores into an application is
						becoming a common requirement. Doing this with a common
						persistence solution is a goal of the EclipseLink project. This
						release introduces EclipseLink's NoSQL support for MongoDB and
						Oracle NoSQL.
					</td>
					<td>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/doc_small.png" />
							<a
								href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/UserGuide/JPA/Advanced_JPA_Development/NoSQL">Documentation</a>
						</div>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/wiki_small.png" />
							<a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Examples/JPA/NoSQL">Example</a>
						</div>
					</td>
				</tr>

				<tr>
					<td colspan="2">
						<h4>JSON</h4>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr
					style="padding:0.5em;margin:0.5em 0.5em 1em 1em;border:1px solid #D9D9D9;background:#EFEFEF;-moz-border-radius:4px;">
					<td valign="top">
						EclipseLink MOXy can now be used for the marshaling
						and unmarshaling of JSON object. Leveraging the same context and
						mappings used within
						the JAXB developers can easily integrate JSON
						usage to their
						applications. This is core infrastructure to the
						JPA-RS feature.
					</td>
					<td>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/doc_small.png" />
							<a
								href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Release/2.4.0/JSONBinding">JSON Binding</a>
						</div>
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/wiki_small.png" />
							<a href="wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Examples/MOXy">Examples</a>
						</div>
					</td>
				</tr>

				<tr>
					<td colspan="2">
						<h4>Cache Invalidation from Database</h4>
					</td>
				</tr>
				<tr
					style="padding:0.5em;margin:0.5em 0.5em 1em 1em;border:1px solid #D9D9D9;background:#EFEFEF;-moz-border-radius:4px;">
					<td valign="top">
						Configuring the invalidation of cached entities based
						on changes applied
						directly to the database finally allows
						developers to build
						systems that minimize stale data in the cache.
						This will allow applications to more heavily rely on caching and
						increase overall performance and scalability.
						This release includes
						an initial implementation that integrates Oracle
						Database's change
						notification.
					</td>
					<td>
						<!--<div> <img src="/eclipselink/images/doc_small.png" /> <a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/DesignDocs/356812">JPA 
							Documentation</a> </div> -->
						<div>
							<img src="/eclipselink/images/wiki_small.png" />
							<a href="http://wiki.eclipse.org/EclipseLink/Examples/JPA/DCN">Example</a>
						</div>
					</td>
				</tr>

			</table>

		</description>

	</section>

